{[%evp 0,28,18,12,50,62,56,34,63,63,68,26,26,30,46,27,50,42,64,28,35,25,8,-19,
15,-36,1,-2,22,0,26]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3
Qc7 7. Qd3 {This move is considered to be quite effective after 6...Bb4, and
it was also employed few times by strong players now.} (7. Nc2 {Like 7.a3,
this retreat is aimed for avoiding the nasty pin along the a5-e1 diagonal.
However, it feels somewhat awkward: the knight was greatly placed in the
centre.} Nc6 8. Be2 ({White can choose another spot for his bishop but after} 
8. Bd3 Ne5 9. f4 Nxd3+ 10. Qxd3 b5 $1 $132 {Black's unopposed light-squared
bishop immediately starts shooting the enemy centre.}) (8. f4 {was played in
more than 20 games. Here I can present the new interesting idea:} d5 $5 $146 {
By making this move Black opens files and diagonal and claims the main
drawback of White's setup: the weakness of g1-a7 diagonal.} 9. e5 ({Another
illustrative line is} 9. exd5 exd5 10. cxd5 Bc5 $1 11. dxc6 O-O $44 {White is
a piece up, but the king is in a big danger. The play might continue:} 12. Be3
Re8 13. Qd2 Bg4 14. h3 Rad8 15. Qf2 Qb6 $1 {with a powerful attack.}) 9... Ne4
10. cxd5 ({White achieves nothing special also with} 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Be3 b6
12. Be2 Bb7 13. O-O Bc5 {Black's active piece play fully compensates for his
structural drawbacks.}) 10... exd5 11. Bd3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bc5 13. Be3 Qa5 {
The weak c3-pawn yields Black a sufficient counterplay.}) 8... Bd6 $1 {An
excellent move: Black prevents both ..0-0 and also f2-f4.} 9. Be3 O-O 10. h3 ({
Or} 10. Qd2 Be5 11. Nd4 b6 12. Rd1 Bb7 $11) 10... Be5 {The positional threat
of ...Bxc3+ is rather annoying, so White is practically forced to retreat his
knight.} 11. Nd4 b6 12. Rc1 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bb7 {Black had the more comfortable
play in Rombaldoni, A - Epishin, V Trieste 2010}) (7. Bg5 {As we will see, the
Bg5 isn't great here.} Be7 8. Rc1 {This is the most challenging move: the
opposition of rook and Qc7 is potentially promising for White.} ({The
alternative} 8. Be2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qd3 {is strongly met by} Ng4 $1 11. Bxg4
Bxg5 {- in the Hedgehog type of positions the unopposed dark-squared bishop
always offers Black a decent play.}) {However, it has a tactical drawback:}
8... Nxe4 $1 9. Bxe7 ({After} 9. Nxe4 Bxg5 10. Nxg5 Qe5+ {White's compensation
is questionable.}) 9... Nxc3 10. Rxc3 Kxe7 11. Be2 {We have been following the
game Ivanov,R - Malyuga,V Zelenograd 2013} {In my opinion, after} Rd8 $146 12.
O-O Nc6 13. Qd2 Kf8 {White's active play should suffice for equality at the
best - after all, Black has no weaknesses.}) (7. f4 {This aggressive move is
rarely made so early. Indeed, after} Bb4 8. e5 (8. Bd3 {meets} b5 $1 9. e5 bxc4
10. Bc2 (10. exf6 cxd3 11. fxg7 Rg8 12. Qxd3 Rxg7 13. O-O Bb7 {took place in 2
games. Although the engine's valuation is 0,00 it looks shaky for White in
light of extremely powerful Bb7.}) 10... Nd5 11. Bd2 Bxc3 12. bxc3 Nc6 {
White didn't have sufficient compensation for a pawn in Velimirovic, D -
Pavlovic, M Subotica 2000}) 8... Ne4 {it is impossible to avoid the damage of
pawn structure on the queenside. For instance,} 9. Qf3 Nxc3 (9... d5 10. exd6 Nxd6
(10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nxd6 12. Ba3 O-O 13. Bd3 Rd8 14. Qh5) 11. a3 Bc5 12. Be3
b6) 10. bxc3 Be7 11. Qg3 g6 12. Bd3 {This was Deschenaux,Y - Illijin,N Biel
2002} {Here I mostly like} b5 $5 $146 13. f5 {White has to play for an attack!}
gxf5 14. O-O Nc6 {In this sharp position Black's chances are by no means worse.
}) (7. Qe2 {This somewhat awkward move was tried by many strong grandmasters,
such are Korchnoi, Ehlvest, Vocaturo and more. Its main idea is provoking ...
d7-d6, and then White can go for a quick g2-g4 push and host his king on the
queenside} Bd6 $1 {Except for preventing f2-f4 Black is also intending to quickly
make his counterplay. In particular, ...Bd6-e5 is a good idea.} 8. g3 Be5 9.
Be3 Nc6 10. Rd1 {This position occurred in Golecki, J - Sliwicki, D Warsaw 2019} {
Here Black can choose between a few reasonable options, but I mostly like:} d6
11. Bg2 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 O-O 13. O-O {. and now} b5 $1 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Nxb5 Qa5
{, followed by Ba6 offers Black an excellent play on the queenside.}) 7... b6 {
I like this flexible choice: the fianchetto will put pressure on White's
centre, while Black can decide how to develop his kingside later.} 8. Qg3 {
This is the main point of White's 7th move - it provokes Black to trade queens
in unfavourable redaction when the h-file will be used by White's rook.} d6 $1
9. Bd3 ({After} 9. Be2 Bb7 10. f3 Nbd7 11. O-O {the presence of Qg3 isn't a
big deal for Black:} h5 $1 {This is a typical counter-attacking move in this
type of position.} 12. Be3 h4 13. Qf2 Be7 14. Rac1 Rc8 15. b4 Qb8 16. Nb3 {
This position arose after standard Hedgehog play in Ibarra Chami, L -
Flores,D Chess.com INT 2021} {Black can benefit from his early extension on
the kingside with} d5 $1 17. cxd5 (17. exd5 h3 18. g3 Bxb4 $132) 17... Bd6 18. f4
Rxc3 19. Rxc3 Nxe4 $132) 9... Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Re1 (11. b3 Be7 12. Bb2 {
was seen in Nepomniachtchi, I - Artemiev, V Almaty 2016} {Here I prefer the
following way of handling the position:} h5 $5 13. Rad1 h4 14. Qe3 Ne5 15. Be2
g5 $1 $132 {Black managed to secure e5 for his knight, so the king feels fine
in the centre.}) 11... Ne5 12. Bf1 Be7 13. b3 O-O 14. Bb2 Ng6 {Black reached a
harmonious position in Fedoseev, V - Artemiev, V Riadh 2017} *

