{[%evp 0,44,19,29,40,50,44,39,24,34,70,46,26,26,46,34,34,44,34,28,20,-9,52,18,
15,8,44,6,6,2,16,16,75,31,36,10,41,34,32,41,41,42,40,45,25,45,0]} 1. e4 c5 2.
Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. Be3 {As after 7.Be2,
White invites Black to pin his queen's knight.} Bb4 8. Qb3 {Only by
sacrificing the central pawn White can try to claim superiority.} ({Toothless
is} 8. Qd3 O-O 9. Be2 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 ({After} 10. Qxc3 Nxe4 11. Qa3 Nc6 12. O-O
d5 {Black doesn't have any problems with development, and White's bishops pair
doesn't overwhelm the pawn.}) 10... d5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. exd5 Nxd5 {Black has
a good play in Hrysogelou,A - Giannoulis,D Petroupoli 2012}) ({Too slow is also
} 8. f3 O-O 9. Rc1 d5 $1 {Black doesn't fear ghosts! The opposition along
the c-file doesn't bother him.} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. Rxc3 Qe5 {
Black's development advantage started to tell in Manelidou, M - Cramling, P
Achaia 2012}) 8... Bc5 {A sensible idea - White's last move diminished his
control of d4, so the Bc5 is well placed.} ({Too risky is} 8... Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3
Nxe4 10. Qa3 {Black cannot castle, while the weakness of dark squares feels
dangerous.}) 9. Na4 {White continues to play in an aggressive manner.} ({
The quieter} 9. Be2 d6 10. O-O O-O {leads to a long positional struggle with
mutual chances} 11. Rad1 ({After} 11. Rac1 Nc6 12. Rfd1 h6 {White struggles to
put further pressure along the d-file, and it looks like Black should be
able to play...e6-e5 in good redaction. For instance,} 13. h3 e5 14. Nf5 Bxf5
15. exf5 Nd4 $11) 11... e5 {This move is vital. Black should activate the
light squares bishop, even though it diminishes control of d5.} 12. Nc2 Bxe3
13. Nxe3 Nc6 {The knight is heading on d4.} 14. Nc2 ({White achieves nothing
special with} 14. Ned5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Qd8 $11) 14... Be6 15. Qa3 Rfd8 $132 {
Black's bishop is superior over Be2, and ...b7-b5 is to follow soon.}) 9... Ba7
({After} 9... Nxe4 10. Bd3 Bxd4 11. Bxd4 Qa5+ 12. Ke2 {White's bishop pair
worth a pawn, to say the least.}) 10. c5 {Obviosuly, White's main strategic
idea is ''squeezing'' Black's queenside.} O-O 11. Nb6 {The most consistent.} ({
The timid} 11. f3 {meets} d5 $1 12. cxd6 Qxd6 13. Rd1 Qe5 14. Be2 b5 15. Nc3
Bb7 {, and Black is fine.}) 11... Bxb6 12. cxb6 Qd8 13. f3 {After all White
wastes a tempo for covering the Pe4.} ({Hardly better is} 13. Rc1 d6 ({Also
possible is} 13... Nxe4 $5 14. Bd3 Nf6 15. O-O Nc6 {White doesn't seem to have
more than sufficient compensation for a pawn here.}) 14. Bd3 e5 15. Nf3 Be6
16. Qa3 Ng4 $132) 13... d5 14. e5 Nfd7 {Currently Black's position is somewhat
cramped, but 2 White's pawns are hanging simultaneously.} 15. f4 Nxb6 16. Nxe6
{White regains the pawn, but at cost of exchanging the strong Nd4.} Bxe6 17.
Bxb6 Qe7 18. Be2 {White has to play accurately - it is necessary to complete
development.} d4 19. Bc4 Nc6 20. O-O ({The endgame, that arises after} 20. Bxe6
Qxe6 21. Qxe6 fxe6 22. O-O Rf5 {Black has a sufficient counterplay along the
f-file. The g7-g5 break is to follow soon.}) 20... Rac8 21. Rac1 Bxc4 22. Rxc4
Qe6 {The strong d-passer offers Black a sufficient counterplay.} *

