{[%evp 0,32,12,33,62,70,63,31,31,25,61,32,32,32,46,32,32,20,7,-5,26,19,13,22,
12,4,14,14,11,11,4,16,27,21,-6]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4
Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. Bd3 {This natural developing move has a big downside: the
Nd4 is unprotected now.} Nc6 {The most logical response: now White has to
either exchange the knights in an unfavourable situation or waste a tempo for
retreating it.} 8. Nxc6 {The most common.} (8. Be3 Ne5 9. h3 {For some reason,
this prophylactic move was seen only in a few games. At the same time, it is
necessary to cover g4.} ({After} 9. O-O $2 Neg4 10. Nf3 Nxe3 11. fxe3 d6 $19 {
White is positionally busted.}) ({Equally bad is} 9. Rc1 $2 Nfg4 $1 10. Bg5 (
10. Qe2 Nxe3 11. Qxe3 Bc5 $19) 10... f6 11. Bh4 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 Ne5 13. Qe2 Qxc4
$19 {Dvirnyy,D - Ortega,L Arvier 2005}) 9... Bb4 10. Rc1 b6 11. O-O (11. a3 Be7
12. O-O Bb7 $132) 11... Bb7 12. Bf4 O-O 13. Re1 Bd6 14. Bg5 Rac8 {Kaidanov,G -
Kharitonov,A Lvov 1985}) (8. Nde2 {looks too passive and hardly poses Black
any problems.} {Indeed, after} Ne5 9. b3 Bc5 10. h3 b6 11. f4 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3
Bb7 {the strong bishops offers Black an excellent play.}) (8. Nf3 {is the
better way of retreating the knight as White has more control over the centre}
Bc5 {There is no way to deviate from placing the bishop most actively} 9. O-O
O-O 10. Bg5 Ng4 $1 {The active Ng4 feels annoying for White's king, so the
next move is practically forced.} 11. h3 Nge5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 $146 ({The
the preceding game saw} 12... Qxe5 $6 13. Qd2 {, and then White can quickly extend
with f2-f4.}) 13. a3 d6 14. b4 Ba7 15. Rc1 Bd7 $132 {The strong Ba7 and
pressure on the c4-pawn fully compensate for White's space advantage.}) 8...
dxc6 {By choosing this recapture Black makes it much easier to develop the
light-squared bishop. Also, the weak d4-spot feels more significant when the
d-file is open.} 9. Be3 {By making this move White prevents Black from taking
control of g1-a7 diagonal.} ({After} 9. O-O Bc5 $1 {Black has a very
comfortable play:} 10. Kh1 e5 11. f4 b5 12. f5 ({After} 12. fxe5 $6 Ng4 13. Qf3
Qa7 {White got under pressure in view of ...Nf2+ threat. Angqvist, T -
Bergqvist, M Stockholm 1994}) 12... h6 {White's bishop isn't allowed on g5!
Black had no problems in Kostin,I - Bareev,E Cheliabinsk 2019}) 9... e5 10. h3
{Otherwise ...Nf6-g4 is very annoying.} Be6 11. O-O Be7 {Both sides are
completing development.} 12. Rc1 ({Toothless is} 12. Na4 O-O 13. Bb6 Qc8 14.
Qe2 {This was McKenzie,P-Constantinou,A Moscow 1994} {Now Black should have
played} Nd7 $146 15. c5 Bd8 $11 {, neutralizing White's space advantage on the
queenside.}) ({The ''academic'' play on the queenside like} 12. c5 O-O 13. a3 {
doesn't really bother Black:} Rfd8 14. Qe2 Nh5 $1 {The strong Nf4 soon allowed
Black to seize the initiative. Maghsoodloo,P - Carlsen,M Chess.com INT 2020})
12... Rd8 13. Qe2 O-O 14. Rfd1 {We have been following the game Pacher,M -
Hrdina,R Prague 2018} {My natural improvement here is} Qa5 $146 15. a3 b5 16.
Nb1 b4 $132 *

