{[%evp 0,38,30,13,44,54,74,45,30,48,58,21,33,33,34,30,73,20,26,21,40,36,30,30,
22,34,51,26,26,34,37,7,15,25,25,25,52,-7,54,37,62]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4
cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. a3 b6 8. Be2 {This move mostly leads
to a transpositions, since after 8.Be3 White puts the king's bishop on e2.
However, there is also an independent case.} ({Worth attention is} 8. f4 $5 Bb7
9. Bd3 {For some reason, this position is practically untested. At the same
time, White's extension in the centre looks promising.} Nc6 $1 {Black should
play actively.} ({Worse is} 9... d6 $6 10. f5 e5 11. Nc2 Nbd7 12. Bg5 $16) 10.
Nxc6 Qxc6 {It makes sense to increase the pressure on the Pe4.} 11. Qe2 ({
Dubious is} 11. O-O $6 Bc5+ 12. Kh1 Bd4 $15 {Oliveira,E - Loureiro,L Sao Paulo
2002}) 11... Bc5 12. Be3 ({The effect} 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. cxd5 Qc7 {poses Black
no problems.}) 12... Bxe3 13. Qxe3 O-O 14. O-O ({The pseudo-aggressive} 14. e5
$2 Qxg2 15. Rg1 Qxb2 16. Rc1 Ne8 {left White with no real compensation for 2
pawns in Bang,A - Zsinka,L Berlin West 1988}) 14... d5 {This freeing move
immediately solves all the problems.} 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Rac1 dxe4 17. Nxe4 Qe6
$11) (8. Qd3 $5 {This move isn't as hamrless as it looks.} Bb7 9. f4 Nc6 10. b4
{There are 4 pawns on the 4th rank - it makes Black's position a bit cramped.}
Be7 ({Too passive is} 10... d6 $6 11. Be3 Be7 12. Rc1 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 $14 {
1-0 (37) Gordievsky,D (2596)-Zakhartsov,V (2470) Moscow 2017}) 11. Be2 O-O 12.
O-O {White is close to completing development, so Black should be in a rush}
a5 $1 {An important resource!} 13. Ndb5 Qd8 14. bxa5 Nxa5 15. e5 Ne8 $132 {
White's pieces are more active, but Black has counterplay against White's
weaknesses on the queenside.}) 8... Bb7 9. Qd3 {The Qd3 feels unsafe, but it is
often connected with an interesting positional idea.} ({The other way to cover
the Pe4 is} 9. f3 Be7 10. O-O (10. Be3 {transposes}) 10... O-O 11. Kh1 d6 12.
b4 {, and then Black can immediately initiate play on the queenside with} b5 $1
13. Bb2 bxc4 14. Rc1 Nbd7 {Luckily for White, there is still a way to maintain
the balance:} 15. Bxc4 $1 Qxc4 16. Na4 $1 ({But not} 16. Nd5 $2 Bxd5 17. Rxc4
Bxc4 $19) 16... Qa2 17. Ra1 Qc4 18. Rc1 $11 {with a repetition.}) 9... Nc6 {
I believe this is the best response to the opponent's last original move. The
threat of ...Ne5 forces White to react.} (9... d6 {is what the strong players
usually prefer but after} 10. b4 Nbd7 11. f4 Rc8 12. Bb2 {White's setup looks
very harmonious when the Bb2 might be useful for attacking measures on the
kingside in the long run.}) 10. Nxc6 (10. f4 $6 {makes White's position
overextended:} Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bc5 12. Qd3 e5 $1 {fixing the weak Pe4} 13. f5 Bd4
{Black took the upper hand in Kvaloy,A - Miezis,N Fagernes 2021}) 10... dxc6 $1
{By choosing the recapture Black claims the drawbacks of Qd3 - it can be
attacked along the d-file.} ({After} 10... Bxc6 11. O-O Be7 12. Be3 O-O 13. Bd4
d6 14. b4 {Black has a solid, but a rather passive position.}) 11. Qg3 {This is
the best way to justify the early Qd1-d3 - White manages to trade queen in
a favourable situation.} ({I've also examined} 11. f4 Rd8 12. Qc2 c5 13. O-O Be7
14. Be3 O-O $11) 11... Qxg3 12. hxg3 Nd7 $1 {A decent manoevre. The Nf6 was
somewhat useless.} ({Less precise is} 12... c5 13. f3 Be7 14. g4 Nd7 15. Be3
$14 {White has some space advantage, and the pressure along the h-file is a
bit annoying.}) 13. Be3 ({The other ambitious try is} 13. f4 Bc5 14. e5 {
, intending to occupy d6} Bd4 $1 15. Ne4 Ke7 16. Nd6 Rab8 $11 {The strong Bd4
offers Black a comfortable play. The Nd6 is strong, but it is unstable, so
White will most likely exchange on b7.}) 13... Bc5 14. Bxc5 Nxc5 15. e5 {
White grabs some space.} ({After} 15. b4 Nd7 16. O-O-O c5 17. Rd6 O-O-O {
the superior Bb7 compensates for White's active rook.}) 15... Nb3 $1 16. Rd1 c5
{d4 is now vacant for the knight.} 17. Rd6 {A draw was agreed in Gorbunova -
Neuburger. Indeed, after} Nd4 18. Rxb6 O-O-O 19. f3 Kc7 {Black has nothing to
worry about.} *

