{[%evp 0,36,30,13,48,48,53,37,32,37,58,33,33,33,34,30,70,33,25,19,38,48,36,29,
64,47,48,36,34,25,35,6,50,30,45,5,7,24,84]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. a3 {By making this move White secures the Nc3
and takes the game to Hedgehog paths. This is by far the top choice by elite
players.} b6 8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3 Be7 10. Be2 (10. Qd2 {mostly doesn't have an
independent value, though I've also examined the following new idea:} d6 11.
Be2 O-O 12. g4 {A very ambitious concept. White is relying on his big space
advantage, so the king stays in the centre for a while.} (12. O-O {transposes
to the main line.}) 12... Nc6 13. Rc1 Nxd4 $1 {A well-timed exchange. Black
prevents the dangerous ideas with Nd5 or Nb5.} 14. Qxd4 Nd7 15. O-O {This move
demonstrates, that White's aggressive plan with g2-g4 wasn't justified.} Rac8 {
Black was doing well in Aagaard, J - Kovacevic, S La Nucia 2021}) 10... O-O 11.
O-O (11. Na4 {also leads to a typical strategic struggle:} d6 12. O-O Nbd7 13.
Rc1 Rfe8 14. b4 Rac8 {This position might be reached with various moves orders.
} 15. Qd2 Qb8 16. Kh1 h5 $1 {By advancing the h-pawn Black puts White's king
under some pressure.} 17. Rfd1 h4 18. Bf1 h3 $132 {Dominguez Perez,L -
Arencibia Rodriguez,W Havana 2007}) (11. Qd2 {is a flexible move, that makes
it possible to play 0-0-0 in some cases. In my opinion, Black should react with
} Nc6 12. O-O (12. O-O-O $6 {runs into} b5 $1 13. cxb5 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 axb5 {
with a dangerous initiative on the queenside.}) 12... Bd6 $1 {It turns out, that
the delay with ...d7-d6 yields Black additional attractive options. Now
White's king is under pressure.} 13. Kh1 {This was Hernandez Sanchez,J -
Crispin Ferreras,D La Vega 2019} ({After} 13. f4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Bc5 15. Qd3 Rad8
{with...d7-d5 to follow Black has nothing to worry about.}) {In my opinion,
Black should have gone for the brave} 13... Bxh2 $146 14. f4 Bg3 15. e5 Ne8 16.
Ne4 Bh4 $132 {The activity of White's pieces compensates for a pawn, but the
Kh1 isn't fully safe as well.}) 11... d6 12. Qd2 Nbd7 13. Rfc1 {This is the
most common choice. By making this move White illustrates, that is he isn't
worried about Black's counterplay on the kingside. In fact, almost all White's
pieces are concentrated on the opposite side.} Rac8 14. b4 ({Another common
plan is} 14. a4 Qb8 15. a5 ({After} 15. Kh1 Ne5 $1 16. b3 Rfd8 $132 {Black is
perfectly prepared for the ...d6-d5 break.}) 15... bxa5 16. Rxa5 {White
managed to create a weakness (a6-pawn), but it took a while and after} Ne5 $1 17.
b3 Rfe8 18. Bf2 d5 {Black was able to solve his problems in Von Meijenfeldt,B
- Arabidze,M Moscow 2016}) ({The prophylactic} 14. Kh1 {can be energetically
met by} h5 $5 $146 15. b4 h4 16. a4 h3 17. gxh3 Ne5 $132 {It is only a matter
of time before Black will activate his light-squared bishop with ...d6-d5.
There is plenty of counterplay.}) 14... Qb8 15. Kh1 {As usual, White hides
the king in the corner and also makes the Be3-g1 retreat possible in some
cases.} (15. Nb3 {is often played with an idea to push ..a4-a5 or even c4-c5
at some point. Also, it makes it tougher for Black to play ...d6-d5.} Rfe8 16.
Kh1 d5 $1 {Still, it seems to work!} 17. cxd5 exd5 18. Bf4 (18. Nxd5 Rxc1+ 19.
Rxc1 Nxd5 20. exd5 Nf6 $11) 18... Bd6 19. Bxd6 Qxd6 $132 {Black was OK in
Kryvoruchko,Y - Baldauf,M Karlsruhe 2020}) ({The standard extension with} 15.
a4 {seems premature in view of} Ne5 16. Nd1 {Kryvoruchko,Y - Ionescu,C
Bucharest 2004} Rfd8 $1 17. a5 d5 {, and the opposition along the d-file
offers Black a sufficient counterplay.}) ({Somewhat slow is} 15. Rab1 h5 16.
a4 h4 17. a5 {This looks like a certain achievement, but Black can do with a
temporary pin} bxa5 18. bxa5 Nc5 19. Nb3 Nfd7 {The pawns on c4 and a5 are also
weak, so Black should be fine.}) 15... h5 $1 {It makes sense to leave bishop
on e7 for a while and develop play on the kingside at once.} (15... Bd8 {is what
was mostly played by strong players, but then} 16. a4 $1 Bc7 17. Rab1 Rfe8 18.
a5 $16 {put Black under strong pressure in Kantans, T - Almasi, Z Germany 2016})
16. Bf2 {This prophylactic move doesn't really prevent Black from pushing the
pawn} ({In comparison to Kantans - Almasi, the a4-a5 push isn't so effective:} 
16. a4 h4 17. a5 bxa5 18. bxa5 Nc5 $132) (16. Rab1 {This attempt to slowly
prepare a4-a5 also offers White no advantage:} h4 17. a4 Ne5 18. Qa2 h3 $132)
16... h4 $1 17. h3 ({After} 17. Bxh4 Nxe4 18. Qe1 Nef6 {Black has great
counter-attacking prospects due to superior control over the centre.}) 17...
Ne5 18. Na4 Bd8 $132 {It is only a matter of time before Black will occupy the
dark squares f4 and g3. The chances were mutual in Barrientos Chavarriaga,S -
Morales, J Buga 2009} *

