{[%evp 0,42,19,38,72,47,55,34,29,47,70,40,38,40,40,27,39,29,34,57,41,30,27,34,
46,38,38,37,39,36,52,32,70,59,74,51,78,39,57,77,134,49,31,15,18]} 1. e4 c5 2.
Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. a3 b6 8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3 Be7
10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O d6 12. Qd2 Nbd7 13. Rac1 {This is the more natural setup.
By placing the rooks on the d and c files White heavily limits the effect of
possible ...d6-d5 break. On the downside, the placement of Rc1 isn't so
effective in case White couldn't push c4-c5 in the long run and also it
practically eliminates the aggressive plan with a3-a4-a5 push.} Rac8 14. Rfd1 (
{Another logical plan is} 14. b4 Qb8 15. Nb3 {This yields White a harmonious
setup when the possibility of ...d6-d5 and ..b6-b5 breaks is very limited. It
is also a top choice by young super-star GM Alireza Firouzja.} ({After} 15. Rc2
Rfe8 16. Rb1 {White is intending to play ..c4-c5 at some point, so Black
should act fast.} h5 $1 17. Na4 h4 18. h3 Bd8 {Black was fine in Warakomska,A
- Abdumalik,Z Wroclaw 2018}) 15... Ne5 $1 {I believe, this is the best moment
for a massive attack on c4.} ({In comparison to other cases, the usual idea
with ...h7-h5 isn't so effective here:} 15... Rfe8 16. Rfd1 h5 17. Bf2 $14 h4
$140 $2 18. Bxh4 Nxe4 19. Nxe4 Bxh4 20. Nxd6 $18) ({Or} 15... h5 16. Bf2 $1 h4
17. Bxh4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxh4 19. Nxd6 $16) 16. Na4 ({Pointless is} 16. Qd4 Nc6 {
, and then} 17. Qxb6 $4 Nd7 {leaves the Qb6 trapped.}) 16... b5 17. Nb6 ({After
} 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Bxb5 Bxe4 $1 19. Be2 Bb7 {the superiority in the centre
provides Black a sufficient counterplay.}) 17... Rcd8 18. cxb5 ({After} 18.
Qc3 d5 $1 19. c5 Nc6 20. exd5 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Rxd5 $11 {the c5-passer is blocked,
and Black benefits from having d5-outpost for the pieces.}) 18... axb5 19. Qc3
(19. Bxb5 $6 d5 {allowed Black to seize the initiative in Tebenkov,V -
Obodenko,A Vladivostok 2016}) 19... d5 20. Qc7 Nc4 $1 21. Qxb8 Rxb8 $132 {
The strong Nc4 compensates for some structural drawbacks.}) ({The prophylactic
} 14. Kh1 Qb8 15. b4 {is another common way of handling the position. As usual,
I mostly like the ambitious} ({After} 15. Rfd1 Rfe8 16. b4 {Black has no
reason for deviating from} h5 $1 {For instance,} 17. Na4 h4 18. Bf1 h3 19. g3
Ne5 20. Nxb6 Nxe4 $1 {Black took over the initiative in Dominguez Perez,L -
Arencibia Rodriguez,W Havana 2007}) 15... h5 $5 16. Bf2 (16. Rfd1 h4 17. Qe1 {
, as in Zimmer,R - Biermann,F Willingen 2017} Rfe8 $1 $146 {can be calmly met
by} 18. h3 Nh5 19. Bf2 Bg5 20. Rc2 d5 $1 {the opposition on the e-file offers
Black a rich counterplay.}) (16. b5 h4 17. a4 Ne5 $132) 16... Ne5 17. Na4 Bd8
{Black isn't only covering the b6-pawn, but also c7 is vacant for the bishop.}
{The play might continue:} 18. c5 bxc5 19. bxc5 Be7 $1 20. cxd6 Rxc1 21. Rxc1
Bxd6 $11) 14... Qb8 15. b4 ({Another common way to regorup the pieces is} 15.
Bf1 Rfe8 16. b4 ({After} 16. Kh1 h5 17. Qf2 Bd8 18. b4 Ne5 $132 {the c4-pawn
was very vulnerable in Golizadeh,A - Nguyen,H Tromsoe 2014}) 16... h5 17. Qf2 {
, as in Karjakin,S - Drygalov,A Chess.com INT 2020} {Here I mostly like the
consistent} h4 $1 $146 18. Na4 Ba8 19. Nb3 d5 $1 {with an excellent
counterplay.}) 15... h5 $1 16. Na4 (16. Nb3 {Dovzhenko, Zubov, 2006} {is also
well met by} h4 $146 17. Bg5 h3 18. gxh3 Ne5 {, and White suffers from few
weak spots.}) 16... h4 $146 {I find this consistent.} ({There is no need to
waste a tempo for covering the b6-pawn:} 16... Ba8 17. Nb3 Bd8 18. Bf4 {
felt somewhat passive for Black in Manea,A - Manolache,M Baia Mare 2021}) 17.
Nb3 ({The quieter} 17. Bf1 Rfe8 18. Qf2 Ba8 19. Nb3 {still runs into} d5 $1 20.
cxd5 Rxc1 21. Rxc1 exd5 {,and Black takes over the initiative.}) 17... d5 $1 {
This is the point! Since White's knight left the centre, this thematic break
is getting more effective now.} 18. cxd5 exd5 19. Bf4 Ne5 $1 {No fear of
ghosts! The pin isn't dangerous.} 20. Nxb6 Rxc1 21. Qxc1 Bd6 $1 {Black has an
excellent counterplay.} *

