{[%evp 0,40,30,25,43,53,40,37,39,39,58,58,78,70,75,33,45,22,13,23,23,-3,-4,-4,
-4,-4,-13,-55,-19,-19,-17,-12,-7,-7,-16,-3,6,-28,0,0,50,14,17]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5 6. Be2 Bb7 7. O-O ({The timid} 7. a3 {
might be followed by f2-f4, but it cannot be considered as a real attempt to
fight for the initiative} Qc7 8. f4 Nc6 9. Be3 ({Or} 9. Nxc6 Bxc6 10. O-O Nf6
11. e5 Bc5+ 12. Kh1 Nd5 {with an excellent play.}) 9... Na5 $5 {This is nearly
the most ambitious way. Black affords wasting few tempi in order to liquidate
the strong light-squared bishop of the opponent.} 10. O-O Nc4 11. Bxc4 Qxc4 12. Nb3
({Over-optimistic is} 12. f5 $6 Nf6 13. fxe6 dxe6 14. e5 {, as in Savchenko, B
- Perunovic,M Chess.com INT 2017} {The simple} Nd7 $1 15. Qh5 g6 16. Qh4 Bg7
$17 {would have put White in a difficult situation.}) 12... Qc7 $1 {Preventing
the nasty ..Na5. Despite the big development advantage, White struggles to
develop any activity against Black's monarch.} 13. Bd4 Nf6 14. e5 Nd5 {The
powerful Bb7 offers Black a decent play. Aaron, M - Rogers, I Hangzhou 1981}) (7.
Bf3 {This somewhat awkward way of covering the central pawn isn't without
merits. In fact, it was successfully employed by many strong grandmasters.} Nc6
{This is what Black plays in most of the chapters, and I see no reason for
deviating from it now.} (7... Qc7 $5 {is somewhat more common and it looks
good too.}) 8. Nxc6 ({After} 8. O-O $6 Ne5 $1 9. Re1 Nf6 $15 {White starts to
suffer from the awkward Bf3. Pandelidis,I - Andreev,E Paleochora 2016}) 8...
Bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 10. e5 {In my opinion, this is practically the only way to
justify the early Be2-f3.} ({After} 10. Re1 Ne7 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Rxe3 O-O $132
{Black reaches a harmonious setup when ...f7-f5 might follow very soon.})
10... Qc7 $1 {It is important to keep an eye on the e4-spot.} 11. Bxc6 Qxc6 12.
a4 b4 13. Qg4 $1 {An important intermediate move. White's knight can be placed
in the centre.} Ne7 14. Ne4 O-O 15. Nf6+ Kh8 {A draw was agreed in the corr
game Van Tricht,M - Stieger,H ICCF email 2014. Indeed, White has nothing
better than forcing perpetual with} 16. Qh4 gxf6 17. Qxf6+ Kg8 18. Bh6 Nf5 19.
Qg5+ $11) 7... b4 8. Na4 ({The brave} 8. Nd5 exd5 9. exd5 {is partly justified
by White's big development advantage. Still, after} Bc5 $1 {making f8 vacant
for the king} 10. Bf3 (10. Re1 Kf8 11. Bf3 {, as in Doghri,N - Maiwald,J Tunis
2000}) 10... Nf6 11. Re1+ Kf8 12. a3 a5) 8... Bxe4 {Black is a pawn up, but
the lack of development makes the situation a bit unstable. Therefore, we
should carefully check all White's possibilities.} 9. Bf3 {The most
straightforward. White is interested in liquidating the only developed piece
of the opponent.} ({After} 9. Be3 Nf6 10. Bf3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 d5 12. Rfe1 Nbd7 {
White didn't have much for a pawn in Libiszewski, F - Romanov, E Moscow 2008}) (
9. Re1 Nf6 10. Bf3 {The opposition of Re1 and the Ke8 is somewhat annoying.} d5
$1 ({The following line well illustrates the potential of White's lead in
development:} 10... Bxf3 $6 11. Qxf3 d5 12. Nf5 $1 Ne4 13. c4 $1 {, and White
has a powerful initiative.}) 11. Bg5 Be7 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. c3 {We have been
following the correspondence game Korchut, A - Skeels, J LSS email 2010} {
In my opinion, the best way of consolidating was} Ra7 $1 $146 14. Qb3 bxc3 15.
Rad1 Rd7 16. bxc3 O-O {White is still a pawn down, so equality isn't
guaranteed.}) (9. c3 Nf6 10. Be3 Nc6 11. f3 (11. Rc1 Be7 12. f3 Nxd4 13. Bxd4
Bc6 14. cxb4 Bxb4 15. Nc5 Nd5 $15 {Weiner,J - Anderson,A ICCF email 2015})
11... Bd5 12. c4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Bc6 14. Nb6 Rb8 15. c5 a5 {Reizniece Ozola,D -
Ilic,Z San Francisco 2000}) 9... Nf6 10. Bxe4 (10. Bg5 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {was seen
in a couple of games. In my opinion, the best way wasn't shown yet:} Ra7 $146
12. Nf5 Nc6 13. Rfe1 h6 14. Bh4 {Black is under some pressure now, but the
next move is very helpful.} Qa5 $1 15. Nxg7+ ({Even worse is} 15. b3 Qd5 16.
Qh3 Ne4 17. Ng3 Ng5 $19) 15... Bxg7 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qxf6 Rg8 18. b3 Qg5 {
Black manages to liquidate into a much better endgame.}) (10. Re1 d5 {
transposes to 9.Re1}) 10... Nxe4 11. Re1 d5 {White must act energetically -
otherwise, Black will complete the development and keep the heavy extra pawn.}
12. Nxe6 {This isn't a real piece sacrifice - White regain it very soon.} ({
In my opinion, the alternative} 12. c4 $5 $146 {is more attractive, but also
in this case Black should be able to stabilize the situation by means of} bxc3
13. Nxc3 Be7 {Black doesn't have to be greedy!} 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Rxe4 O-O 16.
Be3 Qd5 17. Qc2 Bf6 18. b4 Nd7 $11) 12... fxe6 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qe5 Qf6 {
The only, but sufficient response.} 15. Rxe4 Qxe5 16. Rxe5 Kf7 17. Nb6 $146 {
A concrete approach.} ({After} 17. Bg5 $6 Nd7 18. Re3 h6 $15 {Black took over
the initiative in Nitin,S - Jojua,D Abu Dhabi 2018}) 17... Ra7 18. Re3 Rb7 19.
Rf3+ Ke8 20. Be3 Nc6 $132 {The Rf3 is awkward, and Black's central pawns might
be advanced at some point.} *

