{[%evp 0,38,16,28,46,44,53,48,52,55,74,57,80,51,60,46,74,13,9,-6,-12,-1,-1,-11,
28,-6,10,1,42,42,44,-4,-16,-27,-37,-38,-7,-54,23,-5,-44]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3.
d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5 6. g3 Bb7 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O b4 9. Na4 {The main
conitnuation, White sacrifices the central pawn, but Black will have to lose a
couple of tempi.} ({The brave} 9. Nd5 $6 exd5 10. exd5 {puts Black's king in
danger along the e-file, but after} Bc5 $1 11. Re1+ Kf8 {it is possible to do
without castling} 12. Nf5 {The most aggressive move.} (12. Nb3 Bb6 13. c4 d6
14. Bf4 {, as in Gurevich,D - Liou,Y Freemont 2012} {should be met by} a5 $1
$146 {By making this move Black stops the ..c4-c5 idea and also makes a6
vacant for the knight.} 15. Nd4 Bc5 16. a3 Na6 $17) 12... d6 13. a3 {This
looks consistent - White is trying to join the queen's rook in action.} (13.
Bf4 {is what White prefered in most of the games but after} h5 $1 {making some
space for the king and also preparing...Ng4} 14. a3 Ng4 15. Qe2 g6 {White was
already absolutely lost in Rezan, S - Sulava, N Pula 1998}) 13... Bc8 $1 {
Black also activates the useless piece.} 14. axb4 Bxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Bxf5 {White
was practically lost in Pokrupa, M - Kalod, R Havlickuv Brod 2006}) (9. e5 {
leads to major simplifications and doesn't pose Black any problems} Bxg2 10.
Kxg2 bxc3 11. exf6 Qxf6 12. bxc3 Bc5 $1 {The most active way of development.}
13. Be3 ({Worse is} 13. Bf4 $6 O-O 14. Nb3 Qxc3 $17 {Black was just a pawn up
in Navara,D - Ni,H Athens 2001}) 13... O-O 14. Nxe6 {This shot enables White
to regain the pawn} dxe6 15. Bxc5 Rc8 {The damaged pawn chain on the queenside
forced White to struggle for equality. Cagasik,T-Antoniewski,R Czech Republic
2000}) 9... Bxe4 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 11. Re1 (11. c4 {was also tried by many strong
players} bxc3 12. Re1 ({After} 12. bxc3 Be7 13. Rb1 O-O 14. Bf4 Nc6 {Black has
nothing to worry about.}) 12... Nf6 $1 {A calm response.} ({Instead,} 12... d5
$6 13. Nxc3 {, and especially} Nxc3 $2 14. Qh5 $1 {makes White's attack
practically unstoppable, as was demonstrated in dozens of games.}) 13. Qb3 {
Making a threat of 14.Qb7} ({The gambit} 13. Qf3 d5 14. Bg5 cxb2 15. Rad1 Nbd7
16. Nc3 {took place in Demchenko,A - Korobkov,P Sochi 2005} {Now the simple}
Bc5 $146 17. Nxd5 Bxd4 18. Nc7+ Ke7 {would have forced White to struggle for a
draw with} 19. Nd5+) 13... d5 14. Bf4 $146 {White has to play energetically.} (
14. bxc3 $6 Nbd7 15. Be3 Qc8 {White found himself in the ruined position with
no compensation for a pawn. Paredes Galan, A - Yakovich, Y Paris 2005}) 14... Be7
15. Nb6 {This move invites exciting complications.} Ra7 16. Bxb8 Rb7 {White is
a piece up, but it is tough to defend everything.} 17. Ba7 O-O 18. Nc6 {
Very unusual placement of minor pieces!} cxb2 $1 19. Qxb2 ({After} 19. Nxd8
bxa1=Q 20. Rxa1 Rxd8 {only Black can be better.}) 19... Qe8 20. Rac1 Rc7 21.
Qc3 Kh8 $1 {A decent prophylactic move. The threat of 22...Ne4 makes White's
position somewhat uncomfortable. Undoubtedly, Black has full compensation
for material deficit.}) 11... Nc5 $1 {The most accurate choice. Obviously, the
exchange of knights will support the development of Black's pieces.} ({The
following example illustrates well the potential danger of White's lead in
development:} 11... Nf6 $6 {Now this is a wrong retreat} 12. Qf3 $1 d5 13. Bg5
Be7 {Tne natural play by both sides led to this position in Thiel, T - Sax, G
Senden 1998} {White could have developed a stunning attack with} 14. Rxe6 $1
$146 fxe6 15. Nxe6 Qd6 16. Re1 $40) 12. c3 {White is aiming for opening files
on the queenside.} (12. Qf3 $6 {Curiously, this dubious move is the most common
choice in this position.} Ra7 13. Nxc5 Bxc5 14. Nb3 ({The slower} 14. Be3 Qb6
15. Rad1 O-O {allows Black to fully consolidate. For instance,} 16. c3 bxc3 17.
bxc3 {, as in Simonian,H - Vorobiov,E Gyumri 2008} {Now the simple} d6 $146 18.
Rb1 Qc7 $17 {doesn't leave White any compensation for a pawn.}) ({Even worse is
} 14. Nf5 $2 O-O 15. Nxg7 Kxg7 16. Re5 {A desperate attempt to join more
pieces in the attack} d6 17. Rh5 f5 18. Bh6+ Kg8 $19) 14... Bb6 15. Qg4 ({
Hardly better is} 15. Bf4 Qf6 16. Nd2 O-O 17. Ne4 Qf5 18. Nd6 Qg6 $17 {
Bellahcene,B - Sanal,V Kemer 2009}) 15... Qf6 16. Re2 (16. Bg5 Qxf2+ 17. Kh1
O-O 18. Re2 f5 $19) 16... a5 17. Bf4 O-O {Black was a pawn up in better
position. Korchagina,V - Kindinova,E Smolensk 2008}) ({Inlogical is} 12. Nxc5
Bxc5 13. Be3 Qb6 14. a3 Nc6 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. Bxc5 Qxc5 17. axb4 Qxb4 {White
had to fight for equality in Safarli,E - Yakovich,Y Dresden 2007}) 12... Nxa4
13. Qxa4 Be7 $1 {It is time for completing development.} ({The ''greedy''} 
13... bxc3 {runs into} 14. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 15. Rxe6+ Be7 16. Bg5 {, and White
regain the piece. Black's position remains acceptable, but there are no
winning chances.}) 14. cxb4 Qb6 15. b5 O-O 16. Be3 Bc5 17. Rad1 {This position
occured in Kalegin,E - Simonian,H Alushta 2007} (17. bxa6 Rxa6 18. Qc4 d5 $15 {
Thesing, M - Fedorov, A Brasov 2011}) {In my opinion, there was nothing wrong
with the most natural} 17... d5 $146 18. Rc1 Bxd4 19. Bxd4 Qxb5 {White has
some compensation for a pawn due to control over the open file, but Black is
certainly doing well here.} *

