{[%evp 0,30,36,5,51,49,56,38,27,47,79,59,80,74,67,43,43,35,51,42,39,34,75,40,
48,90,88,70,63,31,21,3,34]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5
6. a3 {This somewhat timid move cam be made at different moments, so there are
few possible transpositions.} Bb7 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. Nxc6 ({White can also try to
delay this exchange with} 8. Be3 {, but after} Nf6 {the pressure on the
e4-pawn starts to tell.} 9. Nxc6 ({In case of} 9. Qe2 {Black might acquire the
bishops pair by means of} Ne5 10. f4 Nxd3+ 11. cxd3 Be7 12. O-O O-O $11) 9...
Bxc6 10. O-O ({The immediate} 10. e5 Nd5 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. O-O Qc7 13. f4 Bc5 {
doesn't offer White any advantage either.}) 10... Qc7 11. f4 Be7 12. e5 Nd5 13.
Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Qg4 g6 15. a4 b4 {Black had a decent play due to his strong Bd5
in Florez, L - Jimenez, J Ibague 2017}) 8... Bxc6 9. O-O {This position was
tested many times on the high level. Most often, it arises after 6.0-0, when
a2-a3 is played later.} ({After} 9. Qe2 Bc5 10. Be3 Qb6 {Black reaches a
harmonious setup when the aggressive} 11. Nd5 {only invites simplifications:}
exd5 12. exd5 Bxe3 13. dxc6 dxc6 14. Qxe3+ Qxe3+ 15. fxe3 Nf6 {The endgame was
equal in Yagupov, I - Neverov, V Pardubice 2013}) {Here I can suggest the new
way if development, starting with} 9... Bd6 $5 $146 {Black takes control of
b8-h2 diagonal and provokes the somewhat weakening f2-f4 advance.} ({Instead,} 
9... Bc5 10. Qg4 Qf6 11. Qg3 Qg6 12. Qh3 {feels uncomfortable for Black in
view of poor placement of Qg6.}) 10. Bxb5 {Undubtedly, this is the most
challenging reply - White takes control over dark squares, that is always
dangerous in Kan.} ({After} 10. f4 Ne7 11. Be3 O-O 12. Qh5 {White's setup
looks threatening, but the strong} f5 $1 13. Rad1 Bc7 {allows Black to secure
the king and take over the initiative.}) ({The quieter} 10. Be3 Ne7 11. Qh5 Bc7
$1 12. Rad1 O-O {leads to a long strategic struggle. The play might continue:}
13. e5 g6 14. Qg5 Nf5 15. Bxf5 exf5 16. Qg3 f6 {The strong unopposed Bc6
fully compensates for some structural drawbacks.}) 10... Bxh2+ 11. Kxh2 axb5
12. Qd6 {The presence of Qd6 in Black's camp visually makes his setup a bit
cramped, On the other hand, White's king isn't fully safe, and Black might
potentially make his counterplay with..f7-f5.} ({Equally good is} 12. Qd4 Qh4+
13. Kg1 Ne7 14. Be3 O-O 15. f3 f5 $132) 12... Ne7 13. Be3 O-O 14. f3 Ng6 15.
Rad1 f5 {Black has a sufficient counterplay.} *

