{[%evp 0,26,30,25,43,42,41,39,39,47,58,42,54,29,59,29,27,4,1,-15,-6,-11,16,-9,
-7,-11,7,7,26]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 {This flexible
continuation is equally common to 5.Nc3. By delaying the development of the knight
White makes it less attractive to play ...b7-b5 and also leaves the
possibility of extending in the centre with c2-c4.} Bc5 {Black actively
develops the bishop and forces White to either retreat his knight from the
centre or waste a tempo for defending it.} 6. c3 {In similar to 6.Be3, White
deviates from retreating his knight. However, this way of developing the
knight is more common, and it was even employed a few times by World champion
Magnus Carlsen.} d6 7. O-O (7. Nd2 {was tried by World champion, but it looks
toothless:} Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. a4 e5 10. N4b3 Ba7 11. Nc4 Be6 {Black had a
comfortable position and eventually took the upper hand. Carlsen,M - Caruana,F
Zuerich 2014}) (7. Be3 Nf6 {transposes to 6.Be3}) (7. Qg4 Nf6 8. Qg3 {This
manoeuvre is much more promising in the main Chapters with 6.Nb3 - here the
presence of c3-pawn makes White's development less attractive.} ({The pawn is
poisoned:} 8. Qxg7 $2 Rg8 9. Qh6 e5 $1 10. Nf5 Bxf5 11. exf5 Bxf2+ $1 {White
was quickly crushed in Perez Rodriguez, L - Gonzalez Zamora, J Merida 2014}) 8...
e5 9. Nb3 Ba7 10. Bg5 Be6 {Black's chances were preferable in Delgado Ramirez,
N - Umetsubo,C Florianopolis 2016}) 7... Nf6 8. Qe2 (8. Be3 O-O 9. Nd2 e5 10.
Nc2 Be6 11. Qe2 {, as in Wetscherek,A - Hellmayr,A Germany 2016} {can be
naturally met by} Nbd7 $146 12. Rfd1 Rc8 13. h3 Qb6 {with an active piece play.
}) ({The slower} 8. Kh1 {also traditionally runs into} e5 9. Nb3 Ba7 10. Bg5 h6
11. Bh4 $146 {Keeping the pin seems the most challenging for Black.} ({The timid
} 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. N1d2 O-O 13. Qe2 Nc6 {left White no compensation for
opponent's strong bishops pair in Berelowitsch, A - Svidler, P Moscow 2003})
11... g5 $1 {As it often happens, Black leaves his king in the centre and
starts to extend on the kingside.} 12. Bg3 h5 13. f3 {The only move!} h4 14. Bf2
Bxf2 15. Rxf2 g4 $40 {White's king is under strong attack.}) 8... O-O 9. Bg5 ({
The passive} 9. Nd2 e5 10. Nc2 Bg4 11. Qe1 Re8 $11 {allows Black to quickly
activate his pieces and ...d6-d5 is to follow soon. Perez Rodriguez, L -
Mekhitarian,K ICC INT 2008}) 9... Nbd7 (9... h6 $5 10. Bh4 e5 $13 {is another
decent option.}) 10. Nd2 {Adams, M - Hansen, S Playchess.com INT 2003} {Here I
like the following way of handling the position:} Ne5 $146 11. Kh1 {White
hardly has anything better then ..f2-f4} h6 12. Bh4 Ng6 $1 {This manoeuvre
makes it possible to get rid of the pin without committing with ...g7-g5.} 13.
Bg3 Re8 {Black has a comfortable play.} *

