Nf6 8. c3 ({The immediate} 8. Qe2 {was also tried on the GM's level. In this
case, I suggest the following new idea:} e5 $146 9. Nf5 Bxf5 10. exf5 Bxe3 11.
fxe3 h5 $1 {It makes sense to limit White's activity on the kingside with g2-g4}
12. O-O-O Nbd7 $132 {Black reaches a harmonious setup.}) 8... O-O 9. Qe2 ({
The quieter} 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Bc2 b5 11. a4 bxa4 12. Bxa4 Bb7 $11 {allows Black
to comfortably complete development and put pressure on e4. Kosteniuk, A -
Muzychuk, M Beijing 2014}) 9... e5 {The exchange of bishops makes Black's play
easier.} 10. Nc2 (10. Nf5 Bxe3 11. Nxe3 {leads to the same.}) 10... Bxe3 11.
Nxe3 Nc6 12. O-O ({The ambitious} 12. O-O-O $6 b5 13. Kb1 Rb8 {might backfire
as Black has the better attacking prospects. For instance,} 14. g4 Be6 15. g5
Nd7 16. h4 b4 {with a strong attack.}) 12... Be6 {The weakness of the d6-pawn
is compensated by Black's harmonious piece play.} 13. Rfd1 Qc7 14. a4 {There
is hardly anything better - White stops the possible ..b7-b5.} Rad8 15. Ndc4 h6
16. Bc2 Ne7 $11 {Black was fine in Klein, F - Smirin, I Ohrid 2009} *

