was employed a few times by genius Vishy Anand, but it doesn't seem to refute
Black's setup:} Bxe3 10. Qxe3 Nf6 11. O-O-O ({The quieter} 11. O-O O-O 12. Rad1
Qc7 13. f4 b5 {was comfortable for Black in Goikhman,V - Chekhov,S St
Petersburg 2011}) 11... b5 12. f4 O-O 13. Kb1 {The natural play by both sides
led to this position in Istona,M - Pechac,J Podhajska 2021 Here I suggest} e5
$1 $146 {By fixing the pawn structure Black heavily limits White's attacking
potential as the mobility of minor pieces is restricted.} 14. f5 Rb8 15. g4 ({
After} 15. Rhg1 a5 16. g4 a4 17. Nc1 a3 $1 18. g5 Nh5 {White's king is in
bigger danger!}) 15... Nxg4 16. Qg3 Nf6 17. Rhg1 Ne8 $132 {Black managed to
neutralize White's threats on along the g-file, while ...a7-a5 is to follow
soon.}) ({The ambitious} 9. f4 {can be naturally met by} b5 {I see no reason
for delaying it: the fianchetto is always effective after White play f2-f4.
Also, Black might consider the further extension with ...a6-a5 and b5-b4.} 10.
a4 ({White achieves nothing special also with} 10. O-O Nf6 11. N1d2 e5 $11)
10... bxa4 11. Rxa4 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 {This position occurred in Karjakin, S -
Arencibia Rodriguez,W Beersheba 2005 A significant improvement is} Rb8 $1 $146
{Intending to liquidate the strong bishop by playing ...Nb4. Also, the Nb3 is
pinned now.} 13. O-O {The play might continue:} Nge7 14. Nc3 O-O 15. Rd1 Nb4
16. Qd4 Nec6 {with mutual chances.}) (9. Nc3 {tranposes to 8.Nc3}) (9. Bxa7
Rxa7 10. O-O Nf6 {tranposes to 9.0-0}) 9... Nf6 10. Bxa7 ({Another common way
of handling the position is} 10. c4 {Indeed, the control over the centre makes
White's position rather attractive - Black struggles to play the freeing ...
d6-d5 or ...b7-b5.} O-O 11. Nc3 e5 {At his turn, Black takes an opportunity of
stabilizing the pawn structure in the centre. From now the Bd3 feels passive.}
12. Bxa7 {The most sensible choice - any Black's piece on a7 seems misplaced.}
({In case of} 12. Rfd1 {Black might favourably change the character of
position with} Nd4 $1 13. Bxd4 exd4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Re8 16. Qf3 Qg5 {
The d4-pawn wasn't a weakness, and the strong unopposed Ba7 offers Black a
