Nd5 Re8 15. Kh1 Be6 $11 {Guliyev,N -Ortega,L Frascati 2005}) 12... Rxa7 13. Qe3
{This is definitely th ebest square for the queen.} ({After} 13. Rad1 Be6 14.
Nd5 {Efimenko,Z - Nguyen,H Hungary 2014 Black can take control of d4 with} a5
$146 15. Qe3 Nd7 16. Nd2 Ra8 $132 {with an approximately equal position.}) (13.
Rfd1 Be6 14. Rac1 (14. Qe3 {transposes to 13.Qe3}) 14... Ra8 15. Qe3 Na5 {
was fine for Black in Plaskett,H - Carlsson,M Copenhagen 1981}) 13... Be6 14.
Rfd1 Ra8 {Obviously, there is no reason to leave the rook on a7 for too long.}
15. Be2 {White's intention is clear: the d6-pawn is a clear target, so it
makes sense to double the rooks on the same file.} Rc8 16. Rd2 {The most
consistent.} (16. Rac1 {meets the same reaction} Na5 $1 17. Nxa5 Qxa5 18. Rxd6
Bxc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4 {leads to approximately the same type of position.}) 16...
Na5 $1 {A correct approach - Black has less space, so any exchange makes his
play easier.} 17. Nxa5 Qxa5 18. Rxd6 ({After} 18. b3 b5 19. Rxd6 bxc4 {White
cannot pretend on claiming superiority.}) 18... Bxc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4 20. Rad1 {
This position occurred in Khairullin, I - Stellwagen, D Yerevan 2006 At this
moment Black should neutralize the activity of the opponent's rooks on the
