{[%evp 0,30,33,12,70,46,50,25,25,25,59,9,20,2,2,-3,-3,2,73,77,65,65,66,81,69,
51,69,49,51,28,84,55,89]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. g3 {
This is only 6th White's choice by statistics, but even so it was seen in
hundreds of high-level games. Among the top players, who opt for the early
fianchetto are Carlsen, Anand, Giri, So and others! Indeed, this way of
handling the position looks flexible: White first takes care of kingside pieces,
when the extension with c2-c4 is still possible (this is the main merit of 5.
g3 comparing to 5.Nc3).} d5 {Undoubtedly, the most challenging reply: Since
White delayed Nb1-c3, this standard break in the centre is more effective.} 6.
Nb3 $1 {Undoubtedly, this retreat poses Black the major practical problems.} ({
The naive} 6. Bg2 $6 {runs into} dxe4 $1 7. Bxe4 ({After} 7. O-O f5 $1 8. Nc3
Nf6 {White had no compensation for a pawn in Preuss,F - Andreikin,D Helsingor
2018}) 7... e5 8. Nb3 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Nf6 10. Bg2 Bg4+ 11. f3 Bf5 $36 {White's
setup lacked harmony in Martinez,J - Granda Zuniga,J Cali 2007}) ({Dubious is} 
6. e5 $6 Nc6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Bg2 Qc7 $1 {This position a-la French feels
unfavourable for White since there is no way to comfortably cover the Pe5.} 9.
f4 Bc5 $15) (6. Nf3 {was played by great Vishy, but it doesn't seem to pose
Black serious problems} Nf6 7. exd5 Qxd5 {Not the only, but rather convincing
way: Black isn't obliged to accept the isolated pawn, even though White's
setup isn't perfect here.} 8. Qxd5 Nxd5 9. Bg2 Nc6 10. O-O Be7 $11 {White's
strong light-squared bishop is compensated by well-placed Nd5.}) ({The natural
developing move} 6. Nc3 {has the same downside as 6.Bg2:} dxe4 7. Nxe4 e5 8.
Nb3 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bg4+ $5 {Not the only, but very logical way.} 10. Be2 Bxe2+
11. Kxe2 Nd7 {Black didn't have any problems in the endgame. Vreugdenhil, F -
Lemmers,O Netherlands 2015}) 6... Nf6 ({Riskier is} 6... dxe4 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8.
N1d2 f5 9. f3 $1 {White's development advantage starts to tell here. For
instance,} exf3 10. Nxf3 Nc6 11. Bf4 $36 {Schroeder,J - Smirin,I Riga 2017}) 7.
exd5 exd5 {Black doesn't fear having the isolated pawn: this recapture
allows him to activate the problematic Bc8.} (7... Qxd5 8. Qxd5 Nxd5 9. Bg2 Nc6
10. O-O {leads to a somewhat inferior endgame in view of strong pressure on
the h1-a8 diagonal.}) 8. Bg2 a5 $5 $146 {I find this fresh idea attractive:
Black will either grab some space on the queenside or acquire the b4-spot for his
knight (in case White reacts with 9.a4)} ({After} 8... Nc6 9. O-O Bg4 10. Qd3
$1 $14 {Black doesn't seem to have sufficient compensation for the weak
d5-pawn.}) 9. O-O ({In case of} 9. a4 Bg4 10. Qd3 Nc6 11. O-O Be7 {Black
benefits from provoking a2-a4: White has to do with ...Nc6-b4.} 12. Re1 O-O 13.
c3 (13. Nc3 $2 Nb4 $17) 13... Re8 {The active piece play compensates for the
isolated d5-pawn. It is important, that White cannot put more pressure on it
as c3 isn't vacant for the knight.}) ({The more concrete approach is} 9. Bg5 a4
10. Qe2+ ({After} 10. Nd4 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Nc3 Nc6 {Black has a certain
counterplay. In particular, 13...Qb6 is an annoying idea.}) 10... Be7 11. Bxf6
gxf6 {Black's pawn structure is seriously damaged, but the bishops pair and
superiority on the queenside (due to the a4-pawn) offer him a sufficient
counterplay. For instance,} 12. Nd4 Nc6 13. Nb5 d4 14. O-O h5 15. Nd2 Bg4 {
with mutual chances.}) 9... a4 10. Nd4 Be7 11. Nc3 ({Equally good is} 11. Re1
O-O 12. Be3 Nc6 13. h3 Ne5 {with the idea...Nc4. Black has nothing to worry
about.}) 11... O-O 12. a3 {The most natural reaction - White stabilizes the
situation on the queenside and fixes the a4-pawn, which might be weak in the long
run.} (12. Re1 Nc6 13. Be3 a3 $132) 12... Nc6 13. Be3 Re8 14. h3 ({The
straightforward} 14. Nde2 {meets} Bf5 $1 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Bf6 {with an
excellent play.}) 14... h6 15. Re1 Bf8 $132 {Black has reached a harmonious
setup. A long strategic struggle is ahead.} *

