{[%evp 0,28,25,17,50,44,44,25,25,25,80,46,40,11,31,20,34,23,41,25,24,4,17,-20,
27,-9,-17,-3,-6,-14,4]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nd2 {
By making such a modest move and locking the dark-squared bishop White can
hardly pretend on claiming superiority, but it was tried by many strong
players, including the great David Bronstein. In comparison to 5.Nc3, White
doesn't have to worry about being attacked with ...b5-b4 in future.} d6 {
A harmonious continuation - Black shows his intention to play the Scheveningen
type of positions.} 6. Bd3 ({White achieves nothing special with fianchetto:} 
6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Qc7 8. O-O Be7 9. c4 Nc6 10. Nxc6 ({After} 10. Nc2 O-O 11. b3
b5 $1 {Black can immediately start counter-attacking actions on the queenside.})
10... bxc6 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 a5 $11 {Martinez Orellana,N - Sandipan,C Dresden
2008}) 6... Nf6 7. O-O Nbd7 {The most flexible move - the awkward Nd2 makes
the kingside fianchetto look quite attractive for Black, as there is no pressure
on the d6-pawn.} 8. c4 (8. f4 {is also well met by} g6 $1 9. Kh1 Bg7 10. N2f3
O-O 11. Qe1 e5 {Black had a great play in Perenyi,B - Adamski,J Hajduszoboszlo
1987}) 8... g6 $1 {The most active way of development. In this specific
situation, Black can afford to play both ..d7-d6 and g7-g6.} ({At the same time,
after} 8... Be7 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 Qc7 11. Rc1 {White reaches a harmonious
setup with definite attacking prospects due to the strong Bb2.}) 9. b3 Bg7 10.
Bb2 O-O 11. Rc1 Qc7 12. Kh1 {This prophylactic move is played with an
intention to push f2-f4. There was no other reasonable idea at White's
disposal.} b6 13. f4 Bb7 14. Qe2 e5 $15 {Black has the better coordination
between his pieces, and the e4-pawn feels weak. Fishbein,A - Vyzmanavin,A
Moscow 1989} *

